1096
00:52:55,084 --> 00:52:56,564
None of your beeswax.

1097
00:52:56,608 --> 00:52:58,000
Love her forever?

1098
00:52:58,044 --> 00:52:58,914
Going to get married?

1099
00:52:58,958 --> 00:53:00,220
So what if we do.

1100
00:53:00,264 --> 00:53:01,308
Here's what.

1101
00:53:01,352 --> 00:53:02,962
You're going to mess her up.

1102
00:53:03,005 --> 00:53:05,138
Shut up.

1103
00:53:05,182 --> 00:53:06,879
It's true.

1104
00:53:06,922 --> 00:53:10,187
Kids whose parents get divorced
always get divorced themselves.

1105
00:53:10,230 --> 00:53:11,275
That's baloney.

1106
00:53:11,318 --> 00:53:12,624
It's a fact.

1107
00:53:12,667 --> 00:53:14,234
You're going to make
Karen feel just how

1108
00:53:14,278 --> 00:53:15,453
your dad made your mom feel.

1109
00:53:15,496 --> 00:53:17,063
I am not.

1110
00:53:17,106 --> 00:53:19,152
Sorry, it's statistical.

1111
00:53:22,373 --> 00:53:26,246
CHRIS: Look, I have no
other friends a lot.

1112
00:53:26,290 --> 00:53:30,032
And, well, I don't want anyone
to get hurt, including you,

1113
00:53:30,076 --> 00:53:33,993
So I think that we
should break up.

1114
00:53:34,036 --> 00:53:34,994
But why?

1115
00:53:35,037 --> 00:53:35,951
We're fine.

1116
00:53:35,995 --> 00:53:37,431
I mean--

1117
00:53:37,475 --> 00:53:40,304
[music playing]

1118
00:54:14,207 --> 00:54:15,904
Is it true?

1119
00:54:15,948 --> 00:54:18,080
Kids whose parents
get divorced wind

1120
00:54:18,124 --> 00:54:20,039
up getting divorced themselves?

1121
00:54:20,082 --> 00:54:22,650
Well, yeah, that's
what the statistics say.

1122
00:54:22,694 --> 00:54:23,695
Man

1123
00:54:23,738 --> 00:54:26,959
You can't let it bother you.

1124
00:54:27,002 --> 00:54:29,744
[music playing]

1125
00:54:37,622 --> 00:54:39,624
It's a mess.

1126
00:54:39,667 --> 00:54:41,060
Oh, man.

1127
00:54:41,103 --> 00:54:42,322
Those creeps.

1128
00:54:42,366 --> 00:54:43,236
Look what they did.

1129
00:54:43,280 --> 00:54:44,368
It's not fair.

1130
00:54:44,411 --> 00:54:45,717
There's just too many of them.

1131
00:54:45,760 --> 00:54:47,196
We didn't do it.

1132
00:54:47,240 --> 00:54:48,067
Who's there?

1133
00:54:48,110 --> 00:54:51,070
Come out.

1134
00:54:51,113 --> 00:54:52,332
It's just us.

1135
00:54:52,376 --> 00:54:54,073
What do you want?

1136
00:54:54,116 --> 00:54:55,379
We want to join you guys.

1137
00:54:55,422 --> 00:54:56,945
We have more fun with
you all than Chris

1138
00:54:56,989 --> 00:54:58,425
and wait-for-me Walter.

1139
00:54:58,469 --> 00:54:59,818
But your folks
aren't divorced?

1140
00:54:59,861 --> 00:55:01,080
Who cares?

1141
00:55:01,123 --> 00:55:01,994
We're getting our
butt kicked here.

1142
00:55:02,037 --> 00:55:03,038
We could use the help.

1143
00:55:03,082 --> 00:55:03,909
No way.

1144
00:55:03,952 --> 00:55:05,302
This is our club.

1145
00:55:05,345 --> 00:55:06,390
Louise is right.

1146
00:55:06,433 --> 00:55:08,174
We win or lose this ourselves.

1147
00:55:08,217 --> 00:55:09,262
No one else.

1148
00:55:09,306 --> 00:55:10,611
But we want in.

1149
00:55:10,655 --> 00:55:12,744
Whatever we have to do
to join we'll do it.

1150
00:55:12,787 --> 00:55:13,919
What?

1151
00:55:13,962 --> 00:55:15,529
You'll get your
parents divorced?

1152
00:55:15,573 --> 00:55:16,400
Sure.

1153
00:55:16,443 --> 00:55:17,357
I was just kidding.

1154
00:55:17,401 --> 00:55:18,271
No.

1155
00:55:18,315 --> 00:55:20,012
Wait.

1156
00:55:20,055 --> 00:55:22,231
If that's what they want, maybe
it's better for some of them.

1157
00:55:22,275 --> 00:55:23,102
Wait a minute.

1158
00:55:23,145 --> 00:55:24,016
That's really mean.

1159
00:55:24,059 --> 00:55:25,496
It doesn't have to be.

1160
00:55:25,539 --> 00:55:28,281
Like Sam, his folks
are always fighting.

1161
00:55:28,325 --> 00:55:29,413
He hates it.

1162
00:55:29,456 --> 00:55:30,370
Maybe they'd be
happier divorced.

1163
00:55:30,414 --> 00:55:33,591
[ahem] Oh, sorry Sam.

1164
00:55:33,634 --> 00:55:35,375
No, it's true.

1165
00:55:35,419 --> 00:55:37,856
Well, if it were better.

1166
00:55:37,899 --> 00:55:39,510
And he's not the only one.

1167
00:55:39,553 --> 00:55:42,295
There's lots of people who
would be better off split up.

1168
00:55:42,339 --> 00:55:43,644
Let's do it.

1169
00:55:43,688 --> 00:55:48,388
Prepare to launch
Operation Splitsville.

1170
00:55:48,432 --> 00:55:49,868
[cheers]

1171
00:55:49,911 --> 00:55:53,828
One, two, three, Splitsville.

1172
00:55:53,872 --> 00:55:55,308
Is that him?

1173
00:55:55,352 --> 00:55:57,310
Yeah, that's Sam's dad.

1174
00:55:57,354 --> 00:55:59,094
Sam says he comes
here every two weeks.

1175
00:55:59,138 --> 00:56:00,400
OK, do you know your line?

1176
00:56:00,444 --> 00:56:02,837
OK, how do you know that?

1177
00:56:02,881 --> 00:56:04,273
How do you know that?

1178
00:56:04,317 --> 00:56:07,233
No, no, how do you know that?

1179
00:56:07,276 --> 00:56:09,104
OK, OK, it's not the
Gettysburg Address.

1180
00:56:09,148 --> 00:56:11,933
Come on.

1181
00:56:11,977 --> 00:56:15,589
So anyway, they say his
dad spends all his time

1182
00:56:15,633 --> 00:56:17,896
buying new clothes
and getting haircuts

1183
00:56:17,939 --> 00:56:19,593
instead of looking for work.

1184
00:56:19,637 --> 00:56:21,987
How do you know that?

1185
00:56:22,030 --> 00:56:24,555
Sam's mom told everyone
at the beauty salon.

1186
00:56:24,598 --> 00:56:27,296
My mom was there.

1187
00:56:27,340 --> 00:56:28,559
Hey, we're not done.

1188
00:56:28,602 --> 00:56:30,169
I've got to talk to my wife.

1189
00:56:36,654 --> 00:56:38,743
Is that Leo's dad?

1190
00:56:38,786 --> 00:56:40,527
Yeah, here he comes.

1191
00:56:44,183 --> 00:56:46,359
We're meeting the
Peterson's at 6:00.

1192
00:56:51,582 --> 00:56:52,409
Oh, sorry.

1193
00:57:06,292 --> 00:57:08,425
Excuse me, ma'am.

1194
00:57:08,468 --> 00:57:10,296
Your husband missed this one.

1195
00:57:10,339 --> 00:57:11,123
Thank you.

1196
00:57:15,475 --> 00:57:19,740
I'll make sure he gets
it when he gets home.

1197
00:57:19,784 --> 00:57:22,395
All right, family,
start up your taste buds.

1198
00:57:22,439 --> 00:57:25,267
Dad's super shishkebabs
are on the way.

1199
00:57:25,311 --> 00:57:26,530
Well, it better
not be too spicy.

1200
00:57:26,573 --> 00:57:27,444
You know my stomach.

1201
00:57:27,487 --> 00:57:28,488
Yes, I do, Marlene.

1202
00:57:28,532 --> 00:57:29,707
You tell me that all the time.

1203
00:57:29,750 --> 00:57:31,230
Well, I mean it all the time.

1204
00:57:31,273 --> 00:57:32,927
Um-- uh-- Dad?

1205
00:57:32,971 --> 00:57:35,495
Yeah, what is it, honey?

1206
00:57:35,539 --> 00:57:37,323
Um-- I-- you know--

1207
00:57:37,366 --> 00:57:39,673
I-- uh-- I Forget

1208
00:57:39,717 --> 00:57:41,370
You forget?

1209
00:57:41,414 --> 00:57:42,502
What did you forget?

1210
00:57:42,546 --> 00:57:43,938
What was it, sweetheart?
- Nothing.

1211
00:57:43,982 --> 00:57:45,331
- Did you see something?
- No.

1212
00:57:45,374 --> 00:57:47,420
Oh, honey, you still
got something wait.

1213
00:57:47,464 --> 00:57:49,640
He's forgetting a lot.

1214
00:57:49,683 --> 00:57:51,555
I know, Alzheimer's.

1215
00:57:56,168 --> 00:57:59,084
[choking]

1216
00:57:59,127 --> 00:58:00,085
Water!

1217
00:58:00,128 --> 00:58:04,089
All right, all right.

1218
00:58:04,132 --> 00:58:09,529
What's the matter
with you, moron.

1219
00:58:09,573 --> 00:58:10,878
[beep]

1220
00:58:10,922 --> 00:58:12,010
WOMAN [ON VOICEMAIL]:
Hey, sweet cakes,

1221
00:58:12,053 --> 00:58:15,535
had a fun time the other night?

1222
00:58:15,579 --> 00:58:19,539
Looking forward to seeing You

1223
00:58:19,583 --> 00:58:22,629
Kissy, kissy, see you soon.

1224
00:58:22,673 --> 00:58:24,109
[laughing]

1225
00:58:24,152 --> 00:58:25,066
Here you.

1226
00:58:25,110 --> 00:58:27,025
Thank you, very much, sir.

1227
00:58:27,068 --> 00:58:28,548
Here's yours.

1228
00:58:28,592 --> 00:58:31,856
[music playing]

1229
00:58:42,301 --> 00:58:46,174
Who was that?

1230
00:58:46,218 --> 00:58:47,872
You're sister is cute.

1231
00:58:47,915 --> 00:58:51,832
Half-sister. and all business.

1232
00:58:51,876 --> 00:58:54,835
Come on, get out.

1233
00:58:54,879 --> 00:58:56,837
How could you
go kissing someone

1234
00:58:56,881 --> 00:58:58,143
in the middle of the afternoon?

1235
00:58:58,186 --> 00:58:59,405
I told you I didn't
know who she was.

1236
00:58:59,448 --> 00:59:00,537
Of course you
know who she was.

1237
00:59:00,580 --> 00:59:01,581
She came out of nowhere.

1238
00:59:01,625 --> 00:59:02,756
I'm supposed to believe that?

1239
00:59:02,800 --> 00:59:04,149
I don't believe
that for a minute.

1240
00:59:04,192 --> 00:59:05,542
Suckers, we got them good.

1241
00:59:12,679 --> 00:59:16,465
OK, status report on
Operation Splitsville.

1242
00:59:16,509 --> 00:59:18,250
Sam says his folks
aren't speaking.

1243
00:59:18,293 --> 00:59:22,602
[cheers] And Leo's mom made
his dad sleep on the couch.

1244
00:59:22,646 --> 00:59:24,822
All right.

1245
00:59:24,865 --> 00:59:27,607
Arthur says his mom and dad
won't eat each other's cooking.

1246
00:59:27,651 --> 00:59:31,176
They bought a pizza
five times this week.

1247
00:59:31,219 --> 00:59:32,351
Three new members on the way.

1248
00:59:32,394 --> 00:59:35,833
Operation Splitsville.

1249
00:59:35,876 --> 00:59:37,661
MR ROBERTS: What's
going on here?

1250
00:59:46,626 --> 00:59:47,714
Your my inside woman.

1251
00:59:47,758 --> 00:59:50,587
I need some inside information.

1252
00:59:50,630 --> 00:59:53,894
I may be a teacher, but
I'm not entirely clueless.

1253
00:59:53,938 --> 00:59:56,593
Half the fifth grade won't
talk to the other half.

1254
00:59:56,636 --> 00:59:57,985
And none of them
will talk to me.

1255
01:00:03,687 --> 01:00:06,080
What's going on out there?

1256
01:00:06,124 --> 01:00:08,996
I don't know.

1257
01:00:09,040 --> 01:00:10,781
I'm in fourth grade.

1258
01:00:10,824 --> 01:00:12,913
MRS ROBERTS: Kenneth,
just leave her alone.

1259
01:00:12,957 --> 01:00:14,785
It's OK for you, you
don't have the Cold

1260
01:00:14,828 --> 01:00:16,351
War raging in your classroom.

1261
01:00:16,395 --> 01:00:18,223
Well, Karen can't help you.

1262
01:00:18,266 --> 01:00:21,792
You're just going to have to
take care of your own class.

1263
01:00:21,835 --> 01:00:23,837
What does that mean?

1264
01:00:23,881 --> 01:00:25,709
What are you trying to say?

1265
01:00:25,752 --> 01:00:28,537
Oh, honestly.

1266
01:00:28,581 --> 01:00:30,061
You never cease to amaze me.

1267
01:00:33,107 --> 01:00:35,022
Mom?

1268
01:00:35,066 --> 01:00:36,937
What does smug mean?

1269
01:00:36,981 --> 01:00:40,593
Smug, um-- self-satisfied,
thinking that you're better

1270
01:00:40,637 --> 01:00:42,160
than everyone else.

1271
01:00:42,203 --> 01:00:44,597
Kind of like gloating.

1272
01:00:44,641 --> 01:00:46,730
Why?

1273
01:00:46,773 --> 01:00:50,821
Oh, nothing, just
something I heard Dad say.

1274
01:00:50,864 --> 01:00:51,778
Really.

1275
01:00:51,822 --> 01:00:52,692
Mm, hm.

1276
01:00:59,264 --> 01:01:02,223
MRS ROBERTS: I'm smug am I?

1277
01:01:02,267 --> 01:01:03,703
MR ROBERTS: What?

1278
01:01:03,747 --> 01:01:06,097
[music playing]

1279
01:01:09,709 --> 01:01:11,145
Hi.

1280
01:01:11,189 --> 01:01:13,670
Hi.

1281
01:01:13,713 --> 01:01:16,455
I have a nice time,
but I'm getting fat

1282
01:01:16,498 --> 01:01:19,240
and I don't want a baby.

1283
01:01:19,284 --> 01:01:22,635
I'm sorry, a baby?

1284
01:01:22,679 --> 01:01:23,984
I'm too young.

1285
01:01:24,028 --> 01:01:27,988
So this is-- goodbye.

1286
01:01:28,032 --> 01:01:30,730
I'll never forget you
even when I'm eight.

1287
01:01:36,693 --> 01:01:38,477
[school bell rings]

1288
01:01:41,175 --> 01:01:44,483
James you've always
been an excellent student.

1289
01:01:44,526 --> 01:01:47,138
But this year your grades
have slipped badly.

1290
01:01:47,181 --> 01:01:49,923
Well, Mr. Roberts, there's
been a lot of trouble at home,

1291
01:01:49,967 --> 01:01:51,490
divorcing.

1292
01:01:51,533 --> 01:01:53,622
Yeah, I understand, but
your grades are your grades.

1293
01:01:53,666 --> 01:01:55,755
And you are in real danger
of not passing this year.

1294
01:01:55,799 --> 01:01:58,105
Kenneth, I'm ready to
go home whenever you are.

1295
01:01:58,149 --> 01:01:58,976
Fine.

1296
01:01:59,019 --> 01:02:00,673
Just a sec.

1297
01:02:00,717 --> 01:02:03,197
Bottom line, everything I
said about that test next week

1298
01:02:03,241 --> 01:02:05,069
goes double for you.

1299
01:02:05,112 --> 01:02:05,983
OK?

1300
01:02:06,026 --> 01:02:08,637
OK.

1301
01:02:08,681 --> 01:02:09,943
I'm just saying I'm ready.

1302
01:02:09,987 --> 01:02:12,337
I don't want to sound smug.

1303
01:02:12,380 --> 01:02:14,034
Not that again with the smug.

1304
01:02:14,078 --> 01:02:15,732
I still don't know what
you're talking about.

1305
01:02:15,775 --> 01:02:16,994
Really?
You don't?

1306
01:02:17,037 --> 01:02:19,170
No, tell me.

1307
01:02:23,174 --> 01:02:24,741
What are you talking about?

1308
01:02:24,784 --> 01:02:26,786
Nothing, forget it.

1309
01:02:26,830 --> 01:02:27,700
Hi.

1310
01:02:27,744 --> 01:02:28,745
Hi.

1311
01:02:28,788 --> 01:02:30,572
What's up with your parents?

1312
01:02:30,616 --> 01:02:31,617
Are they arguing?

1313
01:02:31,660 --> 01:02:32,705
Yeah, a lot.

1314
01:02:32,749 --> 01:02:35,099
Bye, James, excuse me.

1315
01:02:35,142 --> 01:02:38,450
I'll be in the club soon, you
know, Operations Splitsville.

1316
01:02:38,493 --> 01:02:39,712
MRS ROBERTS: Look
where you're parked.

1317
01:02:39,756 --> 01:02:41,105
MR ROBERTS: I didn't realize.

1318
01:02:41,148 --> 01:02:43,411
And we can get back together.

1319
01:02:43,455 --> 01:02:45,152
What is she doing.

1320
01:02:45,196 --> 01:02:47,938
MR ROBERTS: Do you have to have
everything in the front seat?

1321
01:02:47,981 --> 01:02:51,463
MRS ROBERTS: Oh,
give me a break.

1322
01:02:51,506 --> 01:02:55,206
[whistle blows]

1323
01:02:55,249 --> 01:02:56,947
Give me your glasses.

1324
01:02:56,990 --> 01:03:03,127
Here it is, the day you've
all been waiting for,

1325
01:03:03,170 --> 01:03:07,827
the big announcement,
the final verdict.

1326
01:03:07,871 --> 01:03:12,136
I've been watching you
all very carefully.

1327
01:03:12,179 --> 01:03:14,616
And I've made my decision.

1328
01:03:14,660 --> 01:03:18,142
This year's most
valuable player is--

1329
01:03:18,185 --> 01:03:19,796
It will be Chris.

1330
01:03:19,839 --> 01:03:21,101
No, no, it'll James.

1331
01:03:23,974 --> 01:03:24,844
Ernie.

1332
01:03:24,888 --> 01:03:25,758
What?

1333
01:03:25,802 --> 01:03:27,064
He sucks.

1334
01:03:27,107 --> 01:03:28,848
But he's the worst
player on the team.

1335
01:03:28,892 --> 01:03:30,067
Wrong.

1336
01:03:30,110 --> 01:03:32,765
He's the only
player on the team.

1337
01:03:32,809 --> 01:03:34,114
I don't know what
the rest of you

1338
01:03:34,158 --> 01:03:37,335
are doing, not passing,
tripping, fighting.

1339
01:03:37,378 --> 01:03:40,860
But Ernie is the only one
among you still playing soccer.

1340
01:03:40,904 --> 01:03:44,864
And that makes him the MVP.

1341
01:03:44,908 --> 01:03:46,344
Yeah.

1342
01:03:46,387 --> 01:03:47,824
Yeah.

1343
01:03:47,867 --> 01:03:48,694
All right.

1344
01:03:51,784 --> 01:03:52,785
Coach, can I talk to you.

1345
01:03:52,829 --> 01:03:54,656
It's no use pleading, James.

1346
01:03:54,700 --> 01:03:55,788
I made my choice.

1347
01:03:55,832 --> 01:03:56,702
I know.

1348
01:03:56,745 --> 01:03:57,921
I have another question.

1349
01:03:57,964 --> 01:03:59,836
OK, shoot.

1350
01:03:59,879 --> 01:04:02,577
There's a lot of
statistics in sports, huh?

1351
01:04:02,621 --> 01:04:04,492
You mean like
kicking distances,

1352
01:04:04,536 --> 01:04:06,103
RBI, stuff like that?

1353
01:04:06,146 --> 01:04:07,582
Yeah, all that stuff.

1354
01:04:07,626 --> 01:04:09,323
It must work, right?

1355
01:04:09,367 --> 01:04:12,674
I mean, otherwise who would
bother figure them out.

1356
01:04:12,718 --> 01:04:14,024
You're losing me, James.

1357
01:04:14,067 --> 01:04:15,373
What are you asking?

1358
01:04:15,416 --> 01:04:17,636
Just that if
statistics say something,

1359
01:04:17,679 --> 01:04:19,464
you should believe it, right?

